                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d927">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/2833.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">American Ambassador</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-02-20T18:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 20, 1912—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Department informed by American Smelting &amp; Refining Co. of an especially
                    serious condition at their plants at Velardena and Asarco. Asarco is in the
                    hands of a drunken mob, and lives of Americans there in constant danger. Make
                    urgent representations to Mexican Government, with usual reservation of
                    reclamation rights, and earnestly request that sufficient troops be sent to the
                    disturbed district to insure order. If the Mexican Government is unable to
                    afford protection, you may in your discretion advise Americans to leave that
                    particular locality.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
